  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'Learning Transferable Component Prototypes for Compositional Zero-Shot Learning via Disentangled Attribute Representations' that addresses the core challenge of modeling variable yet reusable semantic components in CZSL. Our method introduces a Disentangled Prototype Learning (DPL) architecture that decomposes visual representations into two orthogonal spaces: (1) an invariant attribute core — a compact, transferable prototype capturing the essence of an attribute (e.g., 'spotted') independent of the carrier object, and (2) an object-specific modulation field that encodes how the attribute visually manifests when bound to a particular object (e.g., 'spotted' on a 'leopard' vs. 'bag'). These are learned using a sub-class discrimination objective, where each unique attribute-object pair is treated as a sub-class of its parent attribute and object categories. To enforce disentanglement, we employ a dual-branch encoder with a mutual information minimization constraint between the core and modulation components. Crucially, we introduce a Prototype Recombinator Network (PRN), a lightweight meta-network trained via episodic meta-learning to compose new class embeddings by combining frozen core prototypes with appropriate modulation fields—even when neither the full composition nor the modulation field has been seen during training. The PRN learns the rules of compositionality, such as when modulation should be extrapolated or suppressed. During inference, for a novel composition (e.g., 'glossy shoe'), the system retrieves the invariant 'glossy' core prototype, generates or infers a plausible modulation field for 'shoe' using cross-object transfer, and synthesizes the final classifier weight via the PRN. We further augment this with a prototype memory bank updated via momentum contrast, allowing retrieval-free grounding of component knowledge. This enables truly compositional generalization beyond simple linear combinations. The framework is end-to-end trainable and compatible with both standard CZSL and the more challenging RCZSL setting, demonstrating robustness to domain shifts and unseen styles. By explicitly separating reusable cores from contextual adaptations, our method provides interpretability, improved generalization, and direct control over component reuse — a significant step toward human-like conceptual building blocks in vision systems.",
